Decoding ls -l output

steve@linuxsrv:~ $ ls -l

-rw-rw-r-- 1 steve steve 80 oct 24 13:19 sales.data

Permissions -> -rw-rw-r--
Number of Links -> 1 
Owner Name -> steve 
Group Name -> steve
Number of bytes in the file ->  80 
Last modificaion time -> oct 24 13:19 
File Name -> sales.data


1.Listing All Files, Including Hidden Files
-Hidden files begins with a period- sometimes called the "dot files"
Hidden files are not displayed by default.
To show hidden files with ls, use ls -a
Command options can be combined
ls -l -a same as ls -la & ls -al

2.Listing Files by Type
Use ls -F to reveal file types
/ Directory
@ Link
* Executable

Symbolic Links
-A link is a points to the actual file or directory
-Use the link as if it were the file
-A link can be used to create a shortcut
  Use for long file or directory names
  use to indicate the current version of software

 ls -F -> shows the file type


 3. Listing Files by Time and in reverse 
 ls options
 -a -> List all files, including hidden files
 -t -> List files by time, most recent
 -r -> Reverse the order
 -R -> List files recursively
 -d -> List directory name, not contents
--color -> colorize the output
 ls -latr -> Long listing including all files   reverse sorted by time

 
  tree -d -> Check directory structure 
 tree -Cd -> Check directory structure and give visual output

 Spaces in File names







